This paper deals with a fundamental topic in distributed computing, specifically distributed voting. It discusses a new process called two-sample voting and analyzes its performance in regular graphs. This topic falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). Additionally, the paper involves the use of probability theory and graph theory, which are relevant to the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Information Theory (cs.IT), and Graph Theory (cs.GT). Finally, the paper also discusses the concept of eigenvalues, which is relevant to the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE).
